SIMPLE: lydian
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Lydian
<hw>Lyd"i*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>Lydius</ets>, fr. <ets>Lydia</ets>, Gr. <?/.]</ety> <def>Of or
pertaining to Lydia, a country of Asia Minor, or to its inhabitants;
hence, soft; effeminate; -- said especially of one of the ancient Greek
modes or keys, the music in which was of a soft, pathetic, or voluptuous
character.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Softly sweet in <qex>Lydian</qex> measures,⟦br⟧
Soon he soothed his soul to pleasures.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Lydian stone</b></col>, <cd>a flint slate used by the
ancients to try gold and silver; a touchstone. See
<er>Basanite</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lydine</ent>⟦br⟧
